title: "Housing Prices Predictions"¶

Problem¶

The problem our project aims to solve revolves around accurately predicting house prices based on various features provided in the dataset. This predictive model helps stakeholders, such as real estate agents, buyers, and sellers, in estimating the price of a house given its characteristics.

Goal of Collecting this Dataset¶

This dataset provides key features for predicting house prices, including area, bedrooms, bathrooms, stories, amenities like air conditioning and parking, and information on furnishing status. It enables analysis and modelling to understand the factors impacting house datas and develop accurate predictions in real estate markets using both classification and clustering techniques for better understanding and to get the most results out of it.

Source of the Dataset¶

The dataset was sourced from the kaggle website in this URL : https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/harishkumardatalab/housing-price-prediction

General Information¶

  • Number of Attributes: 13
  • Number of Objects: 545
  • Type of Attributes: Numeric, Symmetric Binary, Ordinal.
  • Classes names: Price.

About Dataset¶

This dataset provides comprehensive information for house price prediction, with 13 column names:

  • Price: The price of the house.
  • Area: The total area of the house in square feet.
  • Bedrooms: The number of bedrooms in the house.
  • Bathrooms: The number of bathrooms in the house.
  • Stories: The number of stories in the house.
  • Mainroad: Whether the house is connected to the main road (Yes/No).
  • Guestroom: Whether the house has a guest room (Yes/No).
  • Basement: Whether the house has a basement (Yes/No).
  • Hot water heating: Whether the house has a hot water heating system (Yes/No).
  • Airconditioning: Whether the house has an air conditioning system (Yes/No).
  • Parking: The number of parking spaces available within the house.
  • Prefarea: Whether the house is located in a preferred area (Yes/No).
  • Furnishing status: The furnishing status of the house (Fully Furnished, Semi-Furnished, Unfurnished).

By observing the statistical measures of the dataset attributes we gathered this information:

  • The price of the houses ranges from 1,750,000 to 13,300,000, with a median price of 4,340,000; which means that there are more high prices than there are low prices. Also, the 3rd Quartile is very far from the max value but close to the median which tells us that there might be some outliers.

  • The area of the houses ranges from 1,650 to 16,200 square feet, with a median area of 4,600 square feet; which also means we have more larger areas of houses than smaller areas.

  • The number of bedrooms ranges from 1 to 6, with a median of 3 bedrooms and a 3rd quartile of 3 which means there are fewer houses with more than 3 bedrooms.

  • The number of bathrooms ranges from 1 to 4, with a median of 1 bathroom which means that half, or more than half of the houses in the dataset have only one bathroom.

  • The number of stories ranges from 1 to 4, with a median of 2 stories and the third quartile is also 2 which indicates that the houses are more likely to have 2 or less stories in this dataset.

  • The number of parkings ranges from 0 to 3, with a median of 0 and a 3rd quartile of 0 as well, which shows that it is less likely for a house to have parkings in this dataset.

  • The attributes : mainroad, guestroom, basement, hotwaterheating, prefarea, airconditioning, and furnishing status are character type which cant be analyzed using this method.

Data Visualization¶

1. Scatter plot:¶

A scatter plot is a powerful visualization tool used in data analysis to explore the relationship between two numerical attributes. It presents data points as individual dots on a two-dimensional plane, with one attribute represented on the x-axis and the other on the y-axis. By plotting data in this manner, a scatter plot allows us to visually assess and understand patterns, trends, and correlations between the two attributes.

In [ ]:
#Scatter plot
with(data, plot(area, price, col = price, pch = 23))

a scatter plot consists of individual data points. Each data point represents a specific observation or data entry, with a pair of values (x, y) corresponding to the values of the two variables being compared which are price and area. the data points are forming a diagonal starting at the bottom left to the top right which forms a positive linear relationship which indicates that when the price increases, the area also increases or vice versa which indicates a strong correlation between the two attributes.

2. Histogram:¶

A histogram is a graphical representation commonly used in statistics and data analysis to visualize the distribution of a single numerical variable. It divides the data into intervals, or "bins," and displays the count of data points falling into each bin as vertical bars. The height of each bar represents how many data points are in that bin, giving a clear and visual representation of the data's distribution. Histograms are valuable for understanding the dataset. They help identify patterns like normal distributions, skewness, or multimodal behavior, making them a fundamental tool for data exploration and analysis.

3. Feature selection¶

Feature selection is a process of selecting a subset of relevant features (or attributes) from the original set of features in a dataset. The goal of feature selection is to choose the most relevant and important features, thereby reducing dimensionality, and improving model performance.

we used a random forest model with the cross-validation method to try different size of subsets of predictors(attributes other than the class label), and compute the accuracy of each subset size to see which subset size provides the highest accuracy for our model:

In [ ]:
#Feature Selection

#ensure the results are repeatable
set.seed(7)
# load the library
library(caret)

# define the control using a random forest selection function
control <- rfeControl(functions=rfFuncs, method="cv", number=10)

# run the RFE algorithm
results <- rfe(data[,-1], data[,1], sizes=c(1:12), rfeControl=control)
# summarize the results
print(results)
# list the chosen features
predictors(results)
# plot the results
plot(results, type=c("g", "o"))

Data Mining Task¶

We employed both supervised and unsupervised learning techniques on our dataset (housing prices), which involves classification and clustering methods, as for classification we did a partitioning method called the train-test split, which splits the dataset into two subsets of different ratios, and we implemented three algorithms to form 9 different decision trees.

1. Classification:¶

Classification is the task of assigning labels to data based on its features which is a supervised learning technique. To assess a classification model's performance, we use a train-test split, dividing the data into a training set for model building and a testing set for evaluation. We perform multiple splits, such as 70-30, 80-20, and 90-10, to check the model's consistency and robustness across different data subsets. This approach ensures reliable and generalizable model evaluations and use the information gain(ID3), Gain ratio(C5.0), and Gini index (CART) algorithms on all of the 3 splits.

Dividing the dataset:¶

we used the rsample package because it uses the sampling technique without replacement which can be more biased if it was with replacement.

we divided our dataset into two divisions for each split:

  • for the first split trainData1, testData1 it was a 70-30, we sampled 70% for training dataset and 30% for testing dataset and that is by using the sample() method and specifying the probability to be prob=c(0.7, 0.3).
  • The second split trainData2, testData2 was an 80-20 split 80% for training dataset and 20% for testing dataset.
  • The third split trainData3, testData3 was a 90-10 split, 90% for the training dataset and a 10% for the testing dataset.

1.1 Bulding the tree using Gain Ratio(C5.0).¶

C5.0 is a common algorithm for building decision trees, and the gain ratio is used in the construction of these trees. Gain ratio is a measure that helps to select the best splitting attribute at each node of the decision tree.

When constructing a decision tree, the algorithm considers different attributes or features at each node and chooses the one that maximizes the gain ratio. Gain ratio can be calculated by taking into account the information gain and the intrinsic information of the attribute.

Note:

  • Information Gain (IG): A measure of the effectiveness of an attribute in classifying the data. It is calculated by comparing the entropy of the dataset before and after the split based on an attribute. Entropy is a measure of impurity or disorder in a set of data.
  • Intrinsic Information (II): This is a measure of the amount of uncertainty in a set of data.

Explanation of the code:

we loaded the library of C5.0 and some other libraries for printing the results, built a model using the c5.0 method which uses the C5.0 to construct the model on the selected trainData and we specified 'price~.' which means it would predict the price variable based on all the rest of the attributes.

By using the predict() method we are using the trained model we have built to make predictions on our testData, the type="class" specifies that we want to get class labels as the predictions.

then we evaluated the model by constructing a cofusion matrix using the predicted data and comparing it to the actual class labels of this data. and lastly, we used the plot() method to visualize our decision trees and how they had made decisions, we did that on all of the three splits we have created on step 1.

1.2 Building the Tree using Gini Index(CART).¶

In classification using decision trees, the Gini index is a measure of impurity in a node. It evaluates how often a randomly chosen element would be incorrectly classified. The goal is to minimize the Gini index by making splits that result in more homogenous subsets. A lower Gini index indicates a more pure node, contributing to trying to find an accurate decision tree for classification.

Nodes with a Gini index close to 0 are considered pure, meaning most instances in the node belong to the same class.

Explanation of the code:

  • Firstly, we load the rpart package for the CART algorithm and the rpart.plot for visualizing the decision tree we are going to create.
  • using rpart() method we identifiead a variable 'fit.tree' which will contain our constructed model by applying CART algorithm on our trainData, setting method="class" to indicate that this is a classification task, and 'cp = 0.008' to set the complexity parameter, which is what controls the level of tree complexity and would help avoid overfitting, ad then printng the fit.tree which prints some details about the decision tree model.
  • using rpart.plot() to see how our decision tree looks with the amazing visualization from the rpart package.
  • checking variable importance for each attribute in the dataset to check which feature has the most impact on our predictions and order them accordingly.
  • predicting the class labels using the trained model 'fit.tree' o the testData.
  • and Lastly, creating a confusion matrix to compare the predictions with the actual class labels.

1.3 Building the Tree using Information Gain(ID3 Algorithm):¶

Information Gain is a crucial concept in decision tree algorithms, notably the Iterative Dichotomiser 3 (ID3). ID3 uses Information Gain to choose the most informative attributes for efficient data partitioning (as splitting attributes).

Information Gain measures the reduction in uncertainty achieved by splitting data with a specific attribute, helping ID3 identify the most relevant features. The algorithm builds a decision tree by iteratively selecting attributes that maximize Information Gain, creating decision nodes that effectively classify instances.

ID3's top-down approach, guided by Information Gain, results in interpretable and accurate decision trees. This synergy makes ID3 a foundational algorithm in machine learning for classification tasks.

  • as shown below, we first need to discretize the area attribute to create an effecient model, and since our model's functions are written manually and not pre-defined, it would be easier to predefine a new categorical attribute to construct the models accordingly and for the predictions to be more readable, after doscretizing the attribute we need to re-define the three splits (70-30, 80-20, 90-10) because we have added a new column to the dataset.

Explanation of the code:¶

This R code implements the ID3 (Iterative Dichotomiser 3) algorithm for constructing decision trees. The code consists of several functions:

1. Entropy Calculation:¶
  • The calculate_entropy function computes the entropy of a set of class probabilities. The formula for entropy is applied to each class probability, and the result is summed up with negation.
2. Information Gain Calculation:¶
  • The calculate_information_gain function computes the information gain for a given attribute in the dataset. It involves calculating the entropy of the entire dataset and the weighted sum of entropies for each partition formed by the attribute values.
3. Decision Tree Construction:¶

  • construct_decision_tree recursively builds a decision tree by selecting attributes with the highest information gain(calculated with the information gain formula we have provided) at each node. It stops splitting when a base case is met, either when all instances have the same class or when the maximum depth is reached(we have added maximum depth because the output was too large to be analyzed). It follows these steps:

  • Base Cases:

    • If all instances have the same class, a leaf node is created with that class.
    • If there are no attributes left or the maximum depth is reached, a leaf node with the majority class is created, majority class is claculated by constructing a table to calculate the frequency distribution of the class labels and order them decreasingly and picking the first one.

  • Attribute Selection:

    • Information gains for all available attributes are calculated.
    • The attribute with the highest information gain is selected.

  • Node Creation and Recursion:

    • A tree node is created with the selected attribute.
    • Subtrees are constructed for each unique value of the selected attribute by recursively calling the construct_decision_tree function on the corresponding subsets of data.
4. Printing Decision Tree Structure:¶

The print_decision_tree_structure function provides a simple way to visualize the constructed decision tree structure. It recursively prints the attributes and their values at each level of the tree.

5. Prediction Functions:¶

  • predict_instance Function:

    • Given a decision tree and a single instance, this function predicts the class by traversing the tree.
    • It checks the attribute value of the instance and recursively moves down the tree until a leaf node (class) is reached.

  • predict_decision_tree Function:

    • Applies the predict_instance function to each instance in the dataset and returns a vector of predicted classes.

The last part of the code demonstrates the usage of these functions:

  • It defines a set of attributes to split on.
  • It sets the target class label ("price") and maximum tree depth.
  • A decision tree is constructed using the construct_decision_tree function.
  • Predictions are made on a dataset using the predict_decision_tree function.

This code essentially provides the backbone for implementing the ID3 algorithm for decision tree classification in R.

Overall Execution:¶

  1. A decision tree is constructed using the training data (trainData1, trainData2, and trainData3), and the tree structure is printed using print_decision_tree_structure.

  2. Predictions are made on the test data (testData1, testData2, and testData3) using the decision tree and the predict_decision_tree method.

Note:¶

  • The decision tree construction follows the principles of the ID3 algorithm, where information gain is used for attribute selection, and the tree is grown recursively.

  • The code is designed for simplicity and educational purposes, and it may not include all the optimizations found in more advanced implementations.

# Function to calculate entropy
calculate_entropy <- function(class_probs) {
  -sum(class_probs * log2(class_probs), na.rm = TRUE)
}

# Function to calculate information gain
calculate_information_gain <- function(data, attribute, class_label) {
  # Calculate the entropy of the entire dataset
  entropy_d <- calculate_entropy(table(data[[class_label]]) / nrow(data))

  # Calculate the weighted sum of entropies for each partition
  partitions <- split(data, data[[attribute]])
  entropy_after_split <- sum(
    sapply(partitions, function(partition) {
      (nrow(partition) / nrow(data)) * calculate_entropy(table(partition[[class_label]]) / nrow(partition))
    })
  )

  # Calculate information gain
  information_gain <- entropy_d - entropy_after_split

  return(information_gain)
}

# Function to construct a decision tree with a maximum depth
construct_decision_tree <- function(data, class_label, attributes, max_depth = Inf, depth = 0) {
  # Base case: if all instances have the same class, create a leaf node
  if (length(unique(data[[class_label]])) == 1) {
    return(as.character(unique(data[[class_label]])))
  }

  # Base case: if there are no attributes left or max depth is reached, create a leaf node with the majority class
  if (length(attributes) == 0 || depth >= max_depth) {
    majority_class <- names(sort(table(data[[class_label]]), decreasing = TRUE))[1]
    return(as.character(majority_class))
  }

  # Select the attribute with the highest information gain

  #initializing dataframe of splitting attributes and their information gains
  #  by the length of the attributes sent in the
  # construct_decision_tree() method parameter : 'attributes'
  information_gains_df <- data.frame(
    Attribute = character(length(attributes)),
    InformationGain = numeric(length(attributes))
  )

  #calculating information gain for each attribute 
  # and saving it into the information gain data frame
  for (i in seq_along(attributes)) {
    attribute_to_split <- attributes[i]
    information_gains_df[i, ] <- c(attribute_to_split, calculate_information_gain(data, attribute_to_split, class_label))
  }

  information_gains_df$InformationGain <- as.numeric(information_gains_df$InformationGain)

  selected_attribute <- information_gains_df$Attribute[which.max(information_gains_df$InformationGain)]

  # Create a tree node with the selected attribute
  tree <- list()
  tree$attribute <- selected_attribute
  tree$children <- list()

  # Recursively construct subtrees for each value of the selected attribute
  attribute_values <- unique(data[[selected_attribute]])
  for (value in attribute_values) {
    subset_data <- data[data[[selected_attribute]] == value, ]
    subset_data <- subset_data[, !(names(subset_data) %in% selected_attribute)]  # Remove the used attribute
    subset_attributes <- setdiff(attributes, selected_attribute) # contains all attributes except the selected attribute

    # Recursively construct the subtree
    subtree <- construct_decision_tree(subset_data, class_label, subset_attributes, max_depth = max_depth, depth = depth + 1)

    # Add the subtree to the current node
    tree$children[[as.character(value)]] <- subtree
  }

  return(tree)
}


# function to print the decision tree
print_decision_tree_structure <- function(tree, depth = 0) {
  if (is.character(tree)) {
    cat(rep(" ", depth), " Terminal Node: Class =", tree, "* \n")
  } else {
    cat(rep(" ", depth), " Split on Attribute:", tree$attribute, "\n")

    for (value in names(tree$children)) {
      cat(rep(" ", depth + 2), "Value:", value, "\n")
      print_decision_tree_structure(tree$children[[value]], depth + 4)
    }
  }
}

# variables to be used to construct the tables:
attributes_to_split <- c("area_category", "prefarea", "furnishingstatus", "bedrooms", "bathrooms", 
                         "mainroad", "basement", "parking", "guestroom", "hotwaterheating", 
                         "airconditioning", "stories")

target_class_label <- "price"
max_depth <- 4


# Function to make predictions using the decision tree
predict_decision_tree <- function(tree, data) {
  predictions <- character(nrow(data))
  
  for (i in seq_len(nrow(data))) {
    instance <- data[i, ]
    predictions[i] <- predict_instance(tree, instance)
  }
  
  return(predictions)
}

# Function to predict the class of a single instance
predict_instance <- function(tree, instance) {
  if (is.character(tree)) {
    return(tree)
  } else {
    attribute_value <- instance[[tree$attribute]]
    subtree <- tree$children[[as.character(attribute_value)]]
    return(predict_instance(subtree, instance))
  }
}

Decision Tree Structure Analysis:

The presented decision tree exhibits a hierarchical structure where each node signifies a decision based on a particular attribute. Terminal nodes marked with * denote the predicted class. Let's break down the structure:

  1. Root Node:

    • Initial split determined by the attribute 'area_category'.
    • 'Area' greater than 4500 directs to the left branch; otherwise, the right branch is taken.

  2. Left Branch (area_category > 4500):

    • Further division based on the attribute 'prefarea'.
    • If 'prefarea' is 0, the left subtree is traversed; otherwise, the right subtree is followed.

  3. Left Subtree (prefarea = 0):

    • Continuation of splitting using 'bathrooms', 'airconditioning', and 'furnishingstatus' attributes.
    • Terminal nodes represent predicted classes, denoted by *.

  4. Right Subtree (prefarea = 1):

    • This subtree leads to terminal nodes predicting the class as "High," marked with *.

  5. Right Branch (area_category <= 4500):

    • Further split based on the 'furnishingstatus' attribute.
    • 'Furnishingstatus' being 2 (semi-furnished) directs to the left subtree.

  6. Left Subtree (furnishingstatus = 2 - semi-furnished):

    • Continuation of splitting based on the 'guestroom' attribute.
    • Terminal nodes depict the predicted class with *.

  7. Right Subtree (furnishingstatus = 1 - unfurnished):

    • Further division based on the 'basement' attribute.
    • Terminal nodes signify the predicted class with *.

  8. Middle Subtree (furnishingstatus = 3 - furnished):

    • Further splitting based on the 'parking' attribute.
    • Terminal nodes illustrate the predicted class with *.

Each path from the root to a terminal node represents a unique combination of conditions resulting in a predicted class. For instance, conditions such as 'area_category <= 4500', 'furnishingstatus = 3', and 'parking = 1' lead to the predicted class "High." The tree is constructed through an algorithm aiming to identify the most informative features to predict the target variable 'price' by maximizing information gain at each split.

The decision tree structure illustrates a series of splits based on different attributes, culminating in terminal nodes with predicted classes. Let's delve into the analysis:

  1. Root Node:
    • The initial split is determined by the attribute 'area_category'.
    • If the 'area' is greater than 4500, it progresses to the left branch; otherwise, it follows the right branch.

  2. Left Branch (area_category > 4500):
    • Further division based on the attribute 'prefarea'.
    • If 'prefarea' is 0, it proceeds to the left subtree; otherwise, it advances to the right subtree.

  3. Left Subtree (prefarea = 0):
    • Continues splitting based on the attribute 'bathrooms'.
    • Terminal nodes denote the predicted class, marked with *.

  4. Right Subtree (prefarea = 1):
    • Continues splitting based on the attribute 'bedrooms'.
    • Terminal nodes signify the predicted class, marked with *.

  5. Right Branch (area_category <= 4500):
    • Further division based on the attribute 'furnishingstatus'.
    • If 'furnishingstatus' is 2, it moves to the left subtree; otherwise, it progresses to the right subtree.

  6. Left Subtree (furnishingstatus = 2):
    • Continues splitting based on the attribute 'parking'.
    • Terminal nodes denote the predicted class, marked with *.

  7. Right Subtree (furnishingstatus ≠ 2):
    • Continues splitting based on the attributes 'basement' and 'guestroom'.
    • Terminal nodes denote the predicted class, marked with *.

      Each path from the root to a terminal node represents specific conditions leading to a predicted class. For instance, if 'area_category > 4500', 'prefarea = 1', and 'bedrooms = 4', the predicted class is likely "High." This tree is the result of the algorithm's endeavor to identify the most informative features for predicting the target variable 'price' by maximizing information gain at each split.

Comparison:¶

    • Tree A is relatively straightforward, with splits on 'area_category', 'prefarea', 'bathrooms', 'furnishingstatus'و 'guestroom', and 'parking'.

    • Tree C demonstrates moderate complexity, involving splits on 'area_category', 'prefarea', 'bathrooms', 'basement', 'guestroom', 'parking' and 'bedrooms'.

  • Commonalities:

    • All three trees initiate with a split on 'area_category'.
    • Tree C uniquely incorporates a split on 'basement'.
    • Tree B introduces a distinct split on 'stories'.

2. Clustering:¶

Clustering is a method in unsupervised machine learning that groups similar data points together. This technique is valuable for revealing hidden patterns and structures within datasets, with applications ranging from customer segmentation to image analysis. Clustering involves selecting appropriate algorithms, setting parameters, and interpreting results, making it a crucial tool for uncovering insights in diverse fields.

  • We used K-means technique that represents the clusters by the center of cluster.K-means is a widely-used clustering algorithm in unsupervised learning. It randomly selects 'k' objects as centroids, and assigns data points to the nearest centroid, updates centroids based on mean values, and repeats until convergence.

  • we tried three different k-sizes (2, 4, 8) that we have chose randomly and the corresponding average silhouette for each one of them. The silhouette score is a metric that quantifies how well-separated the clusters are. It ranges from -1 to 1, where a higher score indicates better-defined clusters.

STEP 1: Preprocessing before clustering¶

  • We transformed our categorical attributes to numeric attributes.
  • We dropped the class label to perform efficient clustering.
  • We scaled our dataset, Scaling is a common preprocessing step before applying clustering algorithms, as it helps when features are measured on different scales, like in our case (eg. area is in the range of thousands while bedrooms, bathrooms are in the range of (1-4, 1-3)).

BCubed Algorithm¶

  • We have looked at the computation of the algoritm 'Bcubed_score(L, C, alpha)' in the URL Provided: https://rdrr.io/cran/DPBBM/src/R/BCubed_metric.r
  • We have found that in the internal algorithm they compute Precision and Recall so we have took the part of the code that computed those two values and implemented it as Follows:
In [ ]:
### load the preprocessed data to use the price column in the bcubed function
data2<- read.csv("Dataset/HousingEncoded.csv",header = TRUE,sep=',', stringsAsFactors=T)


if(!require('DPBBM')) {
  install.packages('DPBBM')
  library('DPBBM')
}

becubed_function<-function(L,C){
snL <- length(L)
  snC <- length(C)
  
# define the correctness of the relation between i and j
  Correctness <- matrix(nrow = snL, ncol = snC)
  ncluster <- c()
  ncategory <- c()
  
  for( i in 1:snL ){
    for( j in 1:snC ){
 if((L[i] == L[j]) & (C[i] == C[j])) Correctness[i,j] <- 1
      else Correctness[i,j] <- 0
    }
  }
  
# define the num of each cluster
  for(i in 1:snC){
    ncluster[i] <- length(which(C == C[i]))
  }
  
# define the num of each category
  for(i in 1:snL){
    ncategory[i] <- length(which(L[i] == L))
  }
  
Precision <- mean(rowSums(Correctness) / ncluster)
Recall <- mean(colSums(Correctness)/ncategory)

cat("Precision : " ,Precision ,"\n")
cat("Recall : " ,Recall )}

Findings:¶

We have selected a housing prices dataset that represents houses attributes to help stakeholders know the predictions of house prices that they look for based on the houses' characteristics which can improve the proccess of either looking for a house, or trying to sell one with no time.

To provide the best accurate result possible we have applied some preprocessing techniques that can improve the efficiency of our dataset by making the dataset purer to produce an excellent model hopfully. Additionaly, We performed some data visualization techniques such as boxplot, histogram, barplot, and scatterplot to illustrate the data which can help us understand our data to decide which preprocessing techniques are the most appropriate. Based on the boxplots, we have removed the outliers in each attribute which can badly affect the results. Also, we applied data transformation on our attribute by encoding some of the numerical attributes and the categorical as well, discretized the 'price' which is the class label into 'high' and 'low' intervals to facilitate handling the data. Moreover, we performed feature selection on our dataset to decide which features give the best accuracy which would be used during data mining tasks, the features selected were all the 12 features which we have used to perform our classification and clustering techniques.

Accordingly, we enforced the data mining tasks which are classification and clustering.

For Classification:¶

we used the decision tree method to construct our model, we tried 3 different partitions of training and testing data, and applied 3 different algorithms on each partition to get the best result for construction and evaluation and we concluded the following results:

  • We have notices that the 90-10 split is the best result for Information Gain(ID3 Algorithm) because it Outperformed the other splits having 80.85% of Accuracy, and 80.56% of precision, and the other values as well therefore exceeding the other partitions in performance (see Figure 1).

  • For Gain Ratio(C5.0) we noticed that the 80-20 split was the best partition since it provided the highest accuracy being 77.42% and a high precision as well being 75%, a high sensitivity with a value of 80%, and the highest specificity being 75%, when compared with the other two splits we find it the best suited for our dataset since it provided a range of higher values than the other two partitions, although it wasnt the highest sensitivity but overall it had the best values resulting in best performance (see Figure 1).

  • For Gini Index(CART) we concluded that both the 90-10 split and 80-20 split have high performance but we chose to consider the most balanced and higher sensitivity and specificity among them which is the 80-20 split having sensitivity of 71.11% and a specificity of 81.25% since they both have similar accuracy(90-10 split accuracy= 76.59%, 80-20 split accuracy=76.34%) and the precision of 80-20 split is quite high as well(78.04%) even though it is lower than the 90-10 split(83.33%)(see Figure 1).

  • Among the nine decision trees, we chose the best algorithm along with the best split which is the Gini Index 80-20 split since it had the most balanced values and one of the highest accuracies, and the 80-20 split had the best performance in both the Gini Index and the Gain Ratio. Also the Gini Index showed a good performance in all the 3 partitions with almost-balanced values in every split unlike the two other algorithms, all of its values were ranging approximately from 68% to 83% which is quite balanced for all the 12 values! Although the Gain Ratio 80-20 split decision tree was very competitive we decided to choose the higher range which was the Gini Index 80-20 split decision tree.

For Clustering:¶

we used K-means algorithm with 3 different K that we have chosen randomly to find the optimal number of clusters, we calculated the average silhouette width(ASW), the total within sum of squares(TWSS), the BCubed metrics: precision, and recall for each K, and we concluded the following results:

In K=2:

  • the average sillhouette width(ASW) was : 0.17 (see Figure 2), which was our highest ASW but wasn't considered high enough for clustering in general.
  • the Total Within Cluster Sum of Squares (TWSS) was 4805.668 which was unfortunately the highest TWSS among the three K's and the best should be the least values of TWSS.
  • The BCubed Precision was 65.97% which was quite good and actually the best result out of the three.
  • The BCubed Recall was 68.99% which was also the highest value and a good value overall in Clustering.
  • For Visualization,The red cluster was a bit tighter than the blue cluster but The plot was the best plot among the K's having the most separated clusters (see Figure 3).

Overall K=2 Clusters Performance was moderately good, The highest Performance among the K's.

In K=4:

  • the ASW was : 0.12 (see Figure 2) which was the lowest among them.
  • the TWSS was : 4080.0642 which was the second least, moderate but could be better.
  • the BCubed Precision was 64.25% which is the lowest value among the K's but it wasn't bad at all its moderately good.
  • the Bcubed Recall was 34.06% a very low value but not the lowest, could be improved.
  • For visualisation, we can see a little bit of overlap between the clusters which makes it less efficient, not all the clusters were tight enough (see Figure 4).

overall K=4 is the least likely to be chosen as the best K.

In K=8:

  • the ASW was : 0.15 (see Figure 2) which was pretty close to K=2 : 0.17, the second best value among the K's.
  • the TWSS was : 3140.1555 which was the least value making it the best value compared to the other two K's.
  • The BCubed Precision was: 65.54% which was very close to K=2 value: 65.97% making it rank the second after K=2's precision.
  • The BCubed Recall it was : 21.18% which was the lowest value among the K's.
  • For Visualization, we couldn't analyze the cluster plot because it is too interconnected and almost all clusters share similarities, which makes this clustering K the lowest performance of the three in visualization (see Figure 5).

Overall K=8 had mostly good values compared to K=4 but less efficient than K=2.

In Conclusion, we found that the best K for clustering is K=2 Because it had the highest Average silhouette width being 0.17 and the BCubed metrics: precision(65.97%) and recall(68.99%), also it had the best graphical representation among the three of them. Although K=8 had the lowest total within sum of squares(3140.1555) and a high BCubed Precision(65.54%) and Average silhouette width(0.15), but it had a very low BCubed Recall(21.18%) compared to K=2 and K=4 so we finally chose K=2 as the best K for Clustering (see Figure 2).

Classification VS. Clustering:¶

Based on what we applied of algorithms on both classification and clustering we found that both were very helpful in predicting housing prices, which lead to reach our goal to help stakeholders like real estate agents, and even non-real estate agent people that are interested in housing prices to accurately predict the price of a certain house based on multiple characteristics of the house.

However, we determined the best data mining technique for our dataset which is Classification since it has a higher accuracy compared to the clustering and the reason for that is in supervised learning(Classification) it requires the class label provided in advance unlike unsupervised learning(Clustering) which only predicts which datapoints are closer to each other without knowing what the class label is. Also, in Clustering we noticed that the Average silhouette width for all the K's were on the low side and the total WSS was high for all of them as well, the only acceptable values were only for BCubed precision which also werent high but only moderate, and low values for BCubed Recall as well.
